helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Chris Pedersen, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/13514
According to our system, your account is "not locked." As long as you were connected to the MSOE network when you clicked "lock," the password change should have worked. As a first step, I would recommend connecting to the network and restarting your computer. If this does not work, try logging on using your old password.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: RE: Domain Migration notice
helpdesk-ticket.description:
I did this already. Why am I still getting e-mails about it?
Andrew Dietenberger
From: Helpdesk Sent: Friday, November 18, 2016 11:23 AM To: All Students Subject: Domain Migration notice
[cid:image001.png@01D2418E.AF727100]
Notice: Required Laptop Maintenance – Domain Migration
In order to better support the evolving technology needs of our students, staff, and faculty, MSOE IT department will continue to migrate all domain users from our old domain, MSOE.EDU to our new domain, AD.MSOE.EDU. This change will allow MSOE Helpdesk to better support our campus community with their computing needs, reduce the overall number of technical support issues and better position us for changes in future technology. If you have not dropped off your laptop for a domain migration or you turned in your laptop but you were informed that we could not migrate your laptop during the scheduled group migration, please visit: domainmigration.msoe.edu<http://domainmigration.msoe.edu/> to schedule a maintenance appointment so we can properly migrate your laptop to our new domain. Thank you for your cooperation.
To check which domain you are on and whether you need to come or not please follow these instructions:
1. Simultaneously press the [cid:image002.png@01D2418E.AF727100] keys on your keyboard
2. In the Run dialog that opens enter sysdm.cpl and click OK [cid:image003.jpg@01D2418E.AF727100]
3. The System Properties dialog that opens will tell you which domain you are currently using.
If your computer is on the ad.msoe.edu you are already using the new domain and will not need to migrate your computer.
If you are on the msoe.edu domain (missing the ‘ad.’) your computer will need be migrated. [cid:image004.jpg@01D2418E.AF727100]
For more information, please contact the Helpdesk
No MSOE employee nor any MSOE correspondence will ever ask for your account password.
MSOE IT Helpdesk (414)277-7288 helpdesk.msoe.edu CC Greatroom
Helpdesk Hours Mon-Thurs: 7:30a-7:00p Fri: 7:30a-5:00p Sat-Sun: 10:00a-6:00p Summer Hours Mon-Fri: 8:00a-4:30p

helpdesk-ticket.subject: changes to $PATH on school laptop
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Please note: I have been using commands at the command prompt on Windows for 20 years. The behavior I am seeing is new and seems to be a problem only on my school (Elite x2) tablet.
Some installation software on the new image keeps changing my system’s (superuser) %PATH% setting. I will have it set correctly, then within a month something has deleted entries from it and commands that used to work start failing. This causes serious problems since I need to be able to demo software using the deleted entries in classes. Could Software Center be editing my PATH entry? Is there software that I can install that would monitor changes to PATH and make me approve them explicitly? (That would at least help me locate the offending software.) Is there a way that I can lock %PATH% somehow (such as with a registry entry)? Or do you have other suggestions?
Thanks.
Rob Hasker EECS
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Please note: I have been using commands at the command prompt on Windows for 20 years. The behavior I am seeing is new and seems to be a problem only on my school (Elite x2) tablet.
 
Some installation software on the new image keeps changing my system’s (superuser) %PATH% setting. I will have it set correctly, then within a month something has deleted entries from it and commands that used to work start failing. This causes serious problems since I need to be able to demo software using the deleted entries in classes. Could Software Center be editing my PATH entry? Is there software that I can install that would monitor changes to PATH and make me approve them explicitly? (That would at least help me locate the offending software.) Is there a way that I can lock %PATH% somehow (such as with a registry entry)? Or do you have other suggestions?
 
Thanks.
 
Rob Hasker
EECS

helpdesk-note.body: interesting, sys admin
helpdesk-note.body-html: interesting, sys admin

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Dr. Hasker,
I'm not aware of anything that would remove entries from the path environment variable. I suggest enabling registry auditing to see what process is changing the registry value for the path.
https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/cobold/2011/11/29/monitoring-when-registry-keys-are-modified/ has instructions on how to enable auditing. The key you'll want to monitor is HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager\Environment
Please let me know if you have any further questions.
Thanks,
Chris Hougard MSOE IT Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/13564

helpdesk-note.body:
Hello Xinpeng,
This is happening because you need to first register your account at pwdreg.msoe.edu before you can reset your password through the password reset link pwd.msoe.edu. However, this requires that you know what your current password is. Do you know what your password is? It looks like it was last set last week on the 15th.
Generally the passwords for new students are set to the default password formula. The default password is in the form of Msoe######MMDDYY Capital M, Lowercase soe, followed by your ID Number, and then your birthday in MMDDYY format (so only 2 digits for the year).
Have a great day!

Hi
I can not register at pwdreg.msoe.edu. The system says incorrect user ID or password. I tried all the passwords that I can remember but no one is correct. What can I do?
 
 
Thank you
 
发送自 Windows 10 版邮件应用
 
发件人: helpdesk
发送时间: 2016年11月21日 23:07
收件人: yxptc2@gmail.com
主题: Re: [#INC-13571] Can't reset password
 
Hello Xinpeng,
 
This is happening because you need to first register your account at pwdreg.msoe.edu before you can reset your password through the password reset link pwd.msoe.edu. However, this requires that you know what your current password is. Do you know what your password is? It looks like it was last set last week on the 15th. 
 
Generally the passwords for new students are set to the default password formula. The default password is in the form of 
Msoe######MMDDYY
Capital M, Lowercase soe, followed by your ID Number, and then your birthday in MMDDYY format (so only 2 digits for the year). 
 
Have a great day!
 
 
 
[#INC-13571]

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Andreana,
Thank you for your prompt response. I removed the users as requested. As for the password, it was set when the file you are referencing was created. Whoever created that file, encrypted it with the password so that only the person who has the password can retrieve data from the file. If the password was lost of forgotten, there will be no way to retrieve any emails stored in that archive file.
If you wish to archive current data in the GPE mailbox, you can still perform the archive, but you will need to provide the computer with a different filename. When it asks you to provide a password, you will need to remember it or you will be unable to retrieve emails from it as well. Sorry, there is not anything we can do about the old password.
Regards, Xay Xiong MSOE IT Systems Administrator
------------------------------------------

In order to better support the evolving technology needs of our students, staff, and faculty, MSOE IT department will
be migrating all domain users from our old domain, MSOE.EDU to our new domain, AD.MSOE.EDU. This
change will allow MSOE Helpdesk to better support our campus community with their computing needs, reduce the
overall number of technical support issues and better position us for changes in future technology.

Monday, October 10th :11am- 3pm
If you cannot drop your laptop off during any of the above times please visit: domainmigration.msoe.edu to schedule a maintenance appointment.

2. In the Run dialog that opens enter sysdm.cpl and click OK
3. The System Properties dialog that opens will tell you which domain you are currently using.
If your computer is on the ad.msoe.edu you are already using the new domain and will not need to migrate your computer.
If you are on the msoe.edu domain (missing the ‘ad.’) your computer will need be migrated.
For more information, please contact the Helpdesk
No MSOE employee nor any MSOE correspondence will ever ask for your account password.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Aaron Koepke,
Thank you for contacting IT help desk. Since, the beginning of this school year we have changed the way to update and download software. We use an application called software center which allows to update and install software. You should be able to see software center in "start option" present in task bar. If you don't see software center there, then the following link will guide to you set up software center on your computer.
http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/solution/categories/1000010350/folders/1000015760/articles/1000028740-software-center-issues
P.S. You need to be connected to Global Protect to access software center and even to install software center. Let us know if you you were able to access software center.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hey Aaron,
Thank you for that screenshot, it really helps us with diagnosis when we can see the problem. From the looks of it, you still do not have the most updated version of Software Center. When it is fully updated, it should look something like this:
The process for updating software center happens in the background, for the most part. Follow these steps:
Search "cmd" in the start option, right click on "Command Prompt" and run as administrator and hit "Yes". Type "gpupdate/force" and run the group policy. Restart the computerE Go to "Configuration Manager" in "Control Panel" Go to "Actions" tab and run "Machine Policy Retrieval & Evaluation Cycle" Software Center will work just fine in 30 minutes'
Make sure you are connected to Global Protect while running the gpupdate cycle.
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hey Aaron,

Thank you for that screenshot, it really helps us with diagnosis when we can see the problem. From the looks of it, you still do not have the most updated version of Software Center. When it is fully updated, it should look something like this:
The process for updating software center happens in the background, for the most part. 
Follow these steps:
  1. Search "cmd" in the start option, right click on "Command Prompt" and run as administrator and hit "Yes".
  2. Type "gpupdate/force" and run the group policy.
  3. Restart the computerE
  4. Go to "Configuration Manager" in "Control Panel"
  5. Go to "Actions" tab and run "Machine Policy Retrieval & Evaluation Cycle"
  6. Software Center will work just fine in 30 minutes'

Make sure you are connected to Global Protect while running the gpupdate cycle.

Hi Aaron Koepke, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/13587 Here is a solution for the Windows Update error code that we found:
>>Press WIN+R keys on the keyboard to open the run command. >>In the RUN type services.msc and click on OK. >>Make sure Automatic Updates is set to automatic and >>Background Intelligent Transfer Service is set to automatic. helpdesk-ticket.subject: Voicemail Mailbox Quota Warning
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Your voice mailbox has exceeded the quota warning threshold specified by your administrator.
Current Usage: 11.61 MB Quota Warning Threshold: 11.44 MB Quota Size Limit: 14.06 MB
Please reduce your voice mailbox size by deleting few items from your mailbox. The best way to do this is as follows:
1. Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome 2. Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….” 3. Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password. 4. Click web inbox 5. Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages. 6. Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder. 7. Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window. 8. Give it a minute and it should clear up space. 9. You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.
If problems persist or you have issues logging into the web page, please call the helpdesk at 7288.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Your voice mailbox has exceeded the quota warning threshold specified by your administrator.

Current Usage: 11.61 MB
Quota Warning Threshold: 11.44 MB
Quota Size Limit: 14.06 MB

Please reduce your voice mailbox size by deleting few items from your mailbox. The best way to do this is as follows:

1.    Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome
2.    Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….”
3.    Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password.
4.    Click web inbox
5.    Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages.
6.    Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder.
7.    Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window.
8.    Give it a minute and it should clear up space.
9.    You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.


If problems persist or you have issues logging into the web page, please call the helpdesk at 7288.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Voicemail Mailbox Quota Warning
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Your voice mailbox has exceeded the quota warning threshold specified by your administrator.
Current Usage: 12.65 MB Quota Warning Threshold: 11.44 MB Quota Size Limit: 14.06 MB
Please reduce your voice mailbox size by deleting few items from your mailbox. The best way to do this is as follows:
1. Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome 2. Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….” 3. Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password. 4. Click web inbox 5. Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages. 6. Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder. 7. Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window. 8. Give it a minute and it should clear up space. 9. You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.
If problems persist or you have issues logging into the web page, please call the helpdesk at 7288.

3.    Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password.

8.    Give it a minute and it should clear up space.
9.    You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.


If problems persist or you have issues logging into the web page, please call the helpdesk at 7288.

helpdesk-ticket.description: Dr. Herman currently has a HP desktop xw4400 SN#2UA7430FGF, 2GB RAM running win7. There are two issues driving him to start this replacement process. He is trying to use a program called Meshmixer that will not run because the video card does not support OpenGL. The flatscreen monitor also takes several minutes to warm up first thing in the morning. Dr. Herman is interested in a desktop that will last him 3-5 years and would like to repurpose this current machine to the back room in the CBM.

- Jeremiah Buddenhagen

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Voicemail Mailbox Quota Warning
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Your voice mailbox has exceeded the quota warning threshold specified by your administrator.
Current Usage: 12.38 MB Quota Warning Threshold: 11.44 MB Quota Size Limit: 14.06 MB
Please reduce your voice mailbox size by deleting few items from your mailbox. The best way to do this is as follows:
1. Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome 2. Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….” 3. Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password. 4. Click web inbox 5. Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages. 6. Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder. 7. Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window. 8. Give it a minute and it should clear up space. 9. You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.
If problems persist or you have issues logging into the web page, please call the helpdesk at 7288.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Laptop fan not working correctly: German exchange student
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello,
I am currently one of the students studying abroad in Germany for the year. My new laptop that I had received in the beginning of the semester prior to leaving has developed weird fan behavior. For about two weeks the fan would ramp up to full speed then turn off and would keep doing that over and over again. Yesterday it stopped doing that, but now it sounds like a bike wheel with a playing card stuck in the spokes and is very loud and annoying. I don't have any tools to get to the fan to see if anything is suck inside of it and was wondering if there was anything I could do to fix this without taking the laptop apart.
thanks in advance, Dakota Dunks
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hello,
I am currently one of the students studying abroad in Germany for the year. My new laptop that I had received in the beginning of the semester prior to leaving has developed weird fan behavior.  For about two weeks the fan would ramp up to full speed then turn off and would keep doing that over and over again. Yesterday it stopped doing that, but now it sounds like a bike wheel with a playing card stuck in the spokes and is very loud and annoying.  I don't have any tools to get to the fan to see if anything is suck inside of it and was wondering if there was anything I could do to fix this without taking the laptop apart.  

thanks in advance,
Dakota Dunks

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Dakota Dunks,
So to clarify, you have an HP ZBook G3, you were issued this at the beginning of the 2016-2017 school year and you are a junior? If so, performing a hard reset might be able to fix the problem. You can do this by executing the following steps:
1. Turn off the computer. 2. Unplug any devices such as USB connectors and power cables. 3. Hold down the power button for 15 seconds. 4. Wait 10 seconds. 5. Plug the computer into power and turn the computer back on. Start Windows normally.
Hopefully this fixes things, but please let us know if the problem persists as it might be a more complicated hardware issue.
Respectfully, Sabrina Stangler TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter : @MSOEIT
"We are building a culture of Exceptional Customer Service"

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Voicemail Mailbox Quota Warning
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Your voice mailbox has exceeded the quota warning threshold specified by your administrator.
Current Usage: 13.78 MB Quota Warning Threshold: 11.44 MB Quota Size Limit: 14.06 MB
Please reduce your voice mailbox size by deleting few items from your mailbox. The best way to do this is as follows:
1. Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome 2. Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….” 3. Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password. 4. Click web inbox 5. Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages. 6. Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder. 7. Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window. 8. Give it a minute and it should clear up space. 9. You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.
If problems persist or you have issues logging into the web page, please call the helpdesk at 7288.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Your voice mailbox has exceeded the quota warning threshold specified by your administrator.

Current Usage: 13.78 MB
Quota Warning Threshold: 11.44 MB
Quota Size Limit: 14.06 MB

Please reduce your voice mailbox size by deleting few items from your mailbox. The best way to do this is as follows:

1.    Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu in chrome
2.    Click “advanced” and then “proceed to ucon…….”
3.    Log in using your standard msoe domain credentials and your password.
4.    Click web inbox
5.    Select and delete all, or the majority, of the messages in your inbox, this will be a number of pages.
6.    Then click the “deleted” button near the top left to see the deleted folder.
7.    Then click “empty deleted items” in the upper right of the white window.
8.    Give it a minute and it should clear up space.
9.    You can dial *XXXX , where XXXX is your extension, and it will put you right into your voicemail so you can leave yourself a message to see for sure if it comes through.


If problems persist or you have issues logging into the web page, please call the helpdesk at 7288.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: FW: Please read - accessing your Direct Deposit information has changed
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Good Morning,
Dawn Thibedeau is having trouble accessing my.msoe.edu with her username and password. Can you please help her with this issue?
Thank you.
Tracy Buczek Payroll & Benefits Coordinator 1025 N Broadway Milwaukee, WI 53202 Ph: (414) 277-7136 buczek@msoe.edu<mailto:buczek@msoe.edu>
[xlogo-msoe_75.png]
From: Thibedeau, Dawn Sent: Friday, November 18, 2016 4:03 PM To: Buczek, Tracy <buczek@msoe.edu> Subject: RE: Please read - accessing your Direct Deposit information has changed
I’m not able to log-in with my username and password. Please help when you have time, no rush. Thanks, Dawn
From: Buczek, Tracy Sent: Friday, October 14, 2016 11:46 AM To: All Faculty <AllFaculty@msoe.edu<mailto:AllFaculty@msoe.edu>>; All Staff <AllStaff@msoe.edu<mailto:AllStaff@msoe.edu>> Subject: Please read - accessing your Direct Deposit information has changed
Good Morning,
We are happy to announce that in order to provide more complete information, including year-to-date detail, the process for accessing your direct deposit stubs has changed. Beginning with the October 20, 2016 payroll, direct deposit stubs must be accessed per the instructions below:
1. Go to https://my.msoe.edu/ics.
2. Login with your username and password (same as network/email username and password).
3. Click on “Employees” tab.
4. Under the “Employee Information” heading, click on “Review your pay statements”. [cid:image016.png@01D24962.CDBEEC70][cid:image006.jpg@01D2254B.60D5B980]
5. Under “Pay Date” click on the date of the check you would like to view.
[cid:image018.png@01D24962.CDBEEC70][cid:image015.png@01D2254B.60D5B980]
6. Your direct deposit stub will open in PDF format.
**Please note, to access direct deposit stubs prior to October 20, 2016, you will continue to use the previous method as outlined below:
1. Go to https://my.msoe.edu/ics.
2. Login with your username and password (same as network/email username and password).
3. Click on “Employees” tab.
4. Under the “Payroll Statements” heading, click on “Direct Deposit Stub Web”. [cid:image020.png@01D24962.CDBEEC70][cid:image018.png@01D2254B.60D5B980]
5. Input the check date for the pay stub you would like to display, and click “Generate Report.” IMPORTANT: The exact payroll check date must be entered. If an invalid check date is entered, a blank screen will display.
6. The page will load with a link that says “Direct Deposit Stub Web.” Click this link, and a new window will appear, containing a PDF of the desired pay stub.
Please direct any questions to 414-377-7132 or hrdept@msoe.edu<mailto:hrdept@msoe.edu>.
Thank you! Payroll/Human Resources

From: Buczek, Tracy
Sent: Friday, October 14, 2016 11:46 AM
To: All Faculty <AllFaculty@msoe.edu>; All Staff <AllStaff@msoe.edu>
Subject: Please read - accessing your Direct Deposit information has changed
 
Good Morning,
 
We are happy to announce that in order to provide more complete information, including year-to-date detail, the process for accessing your direct deposit stubs has changed.  Beginning with the October 20, 2016 payroll, direct deposit stubs must be accessed per the instructions below:
 
1.      Go to https://my.msoe.edu/ics.
2.      Login with your username and password (same as network/email username and password).
3.      Click on “Employees” tab.
4.      Under the “Employee Information” heading, click on “Review your pay statements”.
 
5.      Under “Pay Date” click on the date of the check you would like to view.
 
6.      Your direct deposit stub will open in PDF format.
 
 
 
**Please note, to access direct deposit stubs prior to October 20, 2016, you will continue to use the previous method as outlined below:
 
1.      Go to https://my.msoe.edu/ics.
2.      Login with your username and password (same as network/email username and password).
3.      Click on “Employees” tab.
4.      Under the “Payroll Statements” heading, click on “Direct Deposit Stub Web”.
5.      Input the check date for the pay stub you would like to display, and click “Generate Report.” IMPORTANT: The exact payroll check date must be entered. If an invalid check date is entered, a blank screen will display.
6.      The page will load with a link that says “Direct Deposit Stub Web.” Click this link, and a new window will appear, containing a PDF of the desired pay stub.
 
Please direct any questions to 414-377-7132 or hrdept@msoe.edu.
 
Thank you!
Payroll/Human Resources

From: Buczek, Tracy Sent: Monday, November 28, 2016 10:34 AM To: Thibedeau, Dawn <thibedeau@msoe.edu<mailto:thibedeau@msoe.edu>> Subject: RE: Please read - accessing your Direct Deposit information has changed
Hi Dawn,
HR does not have the ability to re-set employee usernames and passwords for my.msoe.edu. I have sent a ticket to the helpdesk; they should be contacting you shortly to resolve.
Thanks!
Tracy Buczek Payroll & Benefits Coordinator 1025 N Broadway Milwaukee, WI 53202 Ph: (414) 277-7136 buczek@msoe.edu<mailto:buczek@msoe.edu>
[xlogo-msoe_75.png]
From: Thibedeau, Dawn Sent: Friday, November 18, 2016 4:03 PM To: Buczek, Tracy <buczek@msoe.edu<mailto:buczek@msoe.edu>> Subject: RE: Please read - accessing your Direct Deposit information has changed
I’m not able to log-in with my username and password. Please help when you have time, no rush. Thanks, Dawn
From: Buczek, Tracy Sent: Friday, October 14, 2016 11:46 AM To: All Faculty <AllFaculty@msoe.edu<mailto:AllFaculty@msoe.edu>>; All Staff <AllStaff@msoe.edu<mailto:AllStaff@msoe.edu>> Subject: Please read - accessing your Direct Deposit information has changed
Good Morning,
We are happy to announce that in order to provide more complete information, including year-to-date detail, the process for accessing your direct deposit stubs has changed. Beginning with the October 20, 2016 payroll, direct deposit stubs must be accessed per the instructions below:
1. Go to https://my.msoe.edu/ics.
2. Login with your username and password (same as network/email username and password).
3. Click on “Employees” tab.
4. Under the “Employee Information” heading, click on “Review your pay statements”. [cid:image019.png@01D2496C.EB7A6B90][cid:image006.jpg@01D2254B.60D5B980]
5. Under “Pay Date” click on the date of the check you would like to view.
[cid:image021.png@01D2496C.EB7A6B90][cid:image015.png@01D2254B.60D5B980]
6. Your direct deposit stub will open in PDF format.
**Please note, to access direct deposit stubs prior to October 20, 2016, you will continue to use the previous method as outlined below:
1. Go to https://my.msoe.edu/ics.
2. Login with your username and password (same as network/email username and password).
3. Click on “Employees” tab.
4. Under the “Payroll Statements” heading, click on “Direct Deposit Stub Web”. [cid:image023.png@01D2496C.EB7A6B90][cid:image018.png@01D2254B.60D5B980]
5. Input the check date for the pay stub you would like to display, and click “Generate Report.” IMPORTANT: The exact payroll check date must be entered. If an invalid check date is entered, a blank screen will display.
6. The page will load with a link that says “Direct Deposit Stub Web.” Click this link, and a new window will appear, containing a PDF of the desired pay stub.
Please direct any questions to 414-377-7132 or hrdept@msoe.edu<mailto:hrdept@msoe.edu>.
Thank you! Payroll/Human Resources

4.      Under the “Employee Information” heading, click on “Review your pay statements”.
 
5.      Under “Pay Date” click on the date of the check you would like to view.
 
6.      Your direct deposit stub will open in PDF format.
 
 
 
**Please note, to access direct deposit stubs prior to October 20, 2016, you will continue to use the previous method as outlined below:
 
1.      Go to https://my.msoe.edu/ics.
2.      Login with your username and password (same as network/email username and password).
3.      Click on “Employees” tab.
4.      Under the “Payroll Statements” heading, click on “Direct Deposit Stub Web”.
5.      Input the check date for the pay stub you would like to display, and click “Generate Report.” IMPORTANT: The exact payroll check date must be entered. If an invalid check date is entered, a blank screen will display.
6.      The page will load with a link that says “Direct Deposit Stub Web.” Click this link, and a new window will appear, containing a PDF of the desired pay stub.
 
Please direct any questions to 414-377-7132 or hrdept@msoe.edu.
 
Thank you!
Payroll/Human Resources

helpdesk-note.body-html: When he opens any of the above programs he gets a pop up saying it will expire in a certain number of days. It has a spot for a product key to be imput.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Daniel
Please follow these steps:
Go to Control Panel > Programs and Features > Uninstall a Program Right click on "Microsoft Office Professional Plus 2013" and click "Change" Select "Enter product key" and continue Enter YC7DK-G2NP3-2QQC3-J6H88-GVGXT
Hit Continue and reboot your computer
You should be able to fix this, let us know if it still persists.
Thank you
Arush Arora Ticketing/ Inventory Specialist (414)277-7288 helpdesk@msoe.edu
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Daniel

Please follow these steps:

  • Go to Control Panel > Programs and Features > Uninstall a Program
  • Right click on "Microsoft Office Professional Plus 2013" and click "Change"
  • Select "Enter product key" and continue
  • Enter YC7DK-G2NP3-2QQC3-J6H88-GVGXT
  • Hit Continue and reboot your computer

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Visitor Check-In Site and Tablet
helpdesk-ticket.description:
New Equipment & IT Service Request:
On behalf of Admissions, I am wondering if IT can create a guest or visitor log-in site where visitors can check-in electronically at the front desk reporting the following information: visiting date, first name, last name, vehicle make, model and year, license plate number, license plate state, and reason for visiting campus/person whom the guest will be seeing.
Each submissions will then be e-mailed to Public Safety so that they are aware of who is visiting and can receive vehicle information instantly. This will allow for a more efficient process for both Admissions and Public Safety.
A tablet provided by IT would be best to place at the front desk/check-in area for families to use.
Please let me know if you have any questions or need clarification on my request.
Thank you,
Chao

helpdesk-ticket.description: Bob works for the radio station. He called in saying he couldn't access his email due to a bad password. He is able to access my.msoe.edu & community. LockOutStatus shows no bad passwords. The last password was set 8/25/16. His password might have expired, but if that were the case, he should not have access to the other services. I tried to have him register at pwdreg.msoe.edu in order to reset his password, but it told him he entered an invalid ID. I asked him to type, "@ad.msoe.edu" after his username, but he still received the same error message.

helpdesk-note.body-html: this is the cache settings in configuration manager. To fix go to Control Panel (in small icon view)->configuration manager->cache. Then click configure settings, click yes. The default is 20000MB based on my machine, and I would recommend that. Emailing user and resolving

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Raunel Albiter, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/13734
This local memory issue is caused by a limit on your machine. To resolve this, please follow the steps below.
1) Click the windows button, and search for "Control Panel", and select it 2) In the window that appears, at the top right, there should be a field labeled "view by", make sure this is set to "Small Icons" 3) Of the icons that appear, click on "Configuration Manager" 4) In the window that appears, select the tab labeled "Cache" and click configure settings 5) Click Yes to allow it to make changes 6) The bottom of the window will no longer be grayed out, and you should see a drag bar next to an entry box. Set the value in the entry box to 20000. 7) Click OK 8) Restart your computer
Once your computer finishes rebooting, you should be able to install MATLAB. Please let us know if these instructions resolved your issue. Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Raunel Albiter,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/13734

This local memory issue is caused by a limit on your machine. To resolve this, please follow the steps below.

1) Click the windows button, and search for "Control Panel", and select it
2) In the window that appears, at the top right, there should be a field labeled "view by", make sure this is set to "Small Icons"
3) Of the icons that appear, click on "Configuration Manager"
4) In the window that appears, select the tab labeled "Cache" and click configure settings
5) Click Yes to allow it to make changes
6) The bottom of the window will no longer be grayed out, and you should see a drag bar next to an entry box. Set the value in the entry box to 20000.
7) Click OK
8) Restart your computer

Once your computer finishes rebooting, you should be able to install MATLAB. Please let us know if these instructions resolved your issue.

Thanks,

2) In the window that appears, at the top right, there should be a field labeled "view by", make sure this is set to "Small Icons"
3) Of the icons that appear, click on "Configuration Manager"
4) In the window that appears, select the tab labeled "Cache" and click configure settings
5) Click Yes to allow it to make changes
6) The bottom of the window will no longer be grayed out, and you should see a drag bar next to an entry box. Set the value in the entry box to 20000.
7) Click OK
8) Restart your computer

Once your computer finishes rebooting, you should be able to install MATLAB. Please let us know if these instructions resolved your issue.

Thanks,
Thomas Schleich
helpdesk@msoe.edu
414-277-7288

Hey Thomas,

You can login to your alumni.msoe.edu email account at http://google.msoe.edu or by entering your email address on Google's login page. Your account is only able to login to Google Apps. helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Beth Slayman,
8 out of the 12 macs were connected to the wireless, on the guest network specifically. If there are a high number of students in the building and devices on guest, the quality of speed could degrade which might account for what you were seeing.
I turned off the wireless on all of them and their speeds were well beyond expectations. In some instances I noticed the macs themselves weren't extremely responsive - if you continue to experience issues with them, I would suggest getting a health test or clean up job on the computers themselves. If you have an outside source that takes care of these devices, I would call them in. If not, if we bought them and are to take care of them, then we should set up a discussion with the Help Desk team to do routine health checks to keep them in good shape.
Otherwise, the network itself seems to be fine.
Thank you,
Samantha
